value.value: Round fusome near the anterior end of the female germline stem cell, in region 1 of the germarium.
Cell that is part of the ovarian sheath. All ovarian sheath cells are found in the median layer of the sheath and they include muscle cells and tracheal cells (Cummings, 1973).
Bundle of Kenyon cell projections that arises from the anterior end of the pedunculus and projects dorsally. It consists of two components: the alpha lobe and alpha' lobe.
A bundle of Kenyon cell projections that arises from the anterior end of the pedunculus and projects medially. It consists of three components: the beta lobe, beta' lobe and gamma lobe.
Cytoplasmic bridge that connects the male or female germline cells in a 16-cell cyst.
Spherical fusome found in spermatocyte cells.
Small and spherical fusome found on the anterior region of the germline stem cell or cystoblast, in region 1 of the germarium. It becomes branched in the progeny of the latter, in the cyst cells.
A mature reproductive cell containing a single set of chromosomes.

Domain that is in the process of forming an anlage and does not yet coincide 1:1 with a mature structure. These domains can be identified based on the expression of genes characteristic of the corresponding anlagen and are typically found in the early blastoderm.

label.value: central brain anlage in statu nascendi

value.value: Anlage in statu nascendi of the embryonic central brain in a stage 5 embryo. It will give rise to the central brain anlage.
Anlage in statu nascendi of the amnioserosa in a stage 5 embryo that will give rise to the amnioserosa anlage.
Anlage in statu nascendi of the foregut in a stage 5 embryo that will give rise to the foregut anlage.
Anlage in statu nascendi of the hindgut in a stage 5 embryo that will give rise to the hindgut anlage.
Anlage in statu nascendi of the visual system in a stage 5 embryo that will give rise to the visual system anlage.

Population of contiguous cells, typically arranged in one plane, that is morphologically indistinct from surrounding cells, but already corresponds to a later organ/tissue and can be identified based on gene expression or lineage tracing (Tomancak et al., 2002; Hartenstein, 2004).

Cells of the early embryo that will become the ectoderm following gastrulation (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). It remains at the surface of the embryo as the endodermal and mesodermal anlagen invaginate (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).
Stable infoldings of plasma membrane, rich in the cytoskeletal proteins F-actin and myosin II, present at the leading edge of membrane invagination during cellularization.

value.value: Anlage of the embryonic foregut.
A(n) anlage that develops into some salivary gland duct primordium.
Anlage of the visual system in the gastrula embryo that will give rise to the visual primordium.
Contiguous region of early embryonic cells that will invaginate during gastrulation to form a region of the endoderm (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).
A(n) anlage that develops into some trunk mesoderm.
A(n) anlage that develops into some clypeo-labral primordium. It develops from some clypeo-labral anlage in statu nascendi.
A(n) anlage that develops into some hypopharynx inclusive primordium. It develops from some hypopharynx anlage in statu nascendi.
A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic/larval copper cell. It develops from some posterior midgut primordium.

Primordium of the midgut interstitial cells. This becomes distinct from the posterior midgut inclusive primordium during stage 11, when its cells delaminate from the tip of the posterior midgut primordium and move postero-ventrally to form a ventral plate of basophilic cells (interstitial cell precursors) wedged between the extending lobes of the posterior midgut primordium. This primordium disappears when its cells intercalate back into the midgut epithelium towards the end of stage 14.
Any primordium (FBbt:00005495) that develops into is part of some anatomical entity (FBbt:10000000) that is part of some circulatory system (FBbt:00005057).
A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic garland cell. It develops from some head mesoderm.
A(n) primordium that develops into some pericardial cell. It develops from some cardiogenic mesoderm.
A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic/larval lymph gland. It develops from some cardiogenic mesoderm.

The primordium of the gonadal sheath. This arises from clusters of cells in parasegments 10, 11 and 12 of the dorsal branch of the fat body/gonad primordium which split off during stage 14 and then cluster around the germ cells.

label.value: embryonic primordium of adult tracheal precursor

value.value: Primordium of the late embryo that will give rise to the embryonic precursor of the adult trachea.

Precursor structure that can be recognized based on its distinct morphology and will give rise to one or more differentiated structures (Tomancak et al., 2002; Hartenstein, 2004). It develops from an anlage and may contain smaller anlage and primordia that will produce substructures (Tomancak et al., 2002).

A hemocyte that is not freely circulating, but is attached to the inner surface of the integument or attached to the imaginal discs. Sessile hemocyte islets are segmentally distributed and often located near crystal cells or along the posterior region of the dorsal vessel, concentrated in 2 denser organ-like clusters. These islets contain plasmatocytes, crystal cells and lamellocyte precursors.

definition.value: The 2 denser areas of sessile hemocytes at abdominal segments A and A9 have been referred to as posterior hematopoietic tissue (PHT) (Kurucz et al., 2007).

value.value: The primordium that will form the embryonic/larval prothoracic gland, a substructure of the embryonic/larval ring gland. It originates in the dorsal ectoderm of T1, from which it segregates during stage 15 to form bilateral clusters near the heart precursors. In late embryogenesis, it partially fuses with the corpus allatum.
A(n) primordium that develops into some dorsal pharyngeal muscle cell. It develops from some dorsal pharyngeal muscle anlage.
A(n) primordium that develops into some hindgut visceral muscle fiber.
A(n) primordium that develops into some foregut visceral muscle fiber.
A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic posterior Malpighian tubule. It develops from some Malpighian tubule primordium.
A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic Malpighian tubule tip cell. It develops from some Malpighian tubule primordium.
A(n) primordium that develops into some hypopharynx proper primordium and some posterior pharyngeal sense organ primordium. It develops from some hypopharynx anlage.
A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic small intestine. It develops from some hindgut proper primordium.
A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic large intestine. It develops from some hindgut proper primordium.
A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic/larval rectum. It develops from some hindgut proper primordium.
A(n) primordium that develops into some esophagus. It develops from some esophagus anlage.

Embryonic structure from which the mushroom body is derived. The development of the mushroom body proceeds as follows: axonogenesis of embryonic Kenyon cells starts late in embryonic stage 14. The axons from these cells extend towards the lateral protocerebral tract (LTP). During stage 16, a second set of Kenyon cell fibers form a second tract, closely apposed to the first. By late stage 16, both tracts extend anteriorly beyond the LTP to form the distal part of the peduncle. These tracts make a sharp medial turn close to the boundary with the deutocerebrum to form the medial lobe. By late stage 17 the vertical lobe has emerged as a collateral outgrowth from the point where these tracts bend. Finally, the calyx forms near to the end of embryogenesis.

value.value: A(n) primordium that develops into some embryonic antennal sense organ. It develops from some antennal anlage.
